# Report on the Prevalence of Spousal Abuse

## Introduction

Spousal abuse, also known as intimate partner violence (IPV), domestic violence, or partner abuse, is a pervasive global issue that affects individuals across all demographics, including gender, age, ethnicity, and socioeconomic status. It encompasses physical, sexual, emotional, verbal, psychological, and economic abuse, as well as controlling and coercive behaviors within intimate relationships. Understanding the prevalence of spousal abuse is critical for informing policy, intervention, and support services aimed at mitigating its impact.

This report provides a comprehensive and evidence-based analysis of how common spousal abuse is worldwide and in specific regions, with a focus on the United States, Canada, and global data. It synthesizes findings from authoritative sources, including government agencies, international organizations, and peer-reviewed research, to offer an objective and detailed account of the prevalence and characteristics of spousal abuse.

## Global Prevalence of Spousal Abuse

### General Estimates

According to the World Health Organization (WHO), approximately 30% of women worldwide who have been in a relationship report experiencing physical and/or sexual violence by an intimate partner at some point in their lives ([WHO](https://www.who.int/news-room/fact-sheets/detail/violence-against-women)). This figure highlights the widespread nature of the problem across diverse cultures and societies.

A UN report further specifies that globally, one in three women has experienced some form of physical or sexual violence, mostly by an intimate partner ([Sparknews, 2021](https://www.sparknews.com/news/2021-06-22-facts-figures-global-domestic-violence/)). The prevalence varies by region, with estimates ranging from approximately 20% in the Western Pacific to 33% in the WHO African and Southeast Asia regions.

