### Impact of Societal Acceptance

Research indicates that societal acceptance of domestic violence correlates with its prevalence. For example, a study covering 49 low- and middle-income countries found that on average, 36% of people find domestic violence justifiable under certain circumstances, with South Asia showing the highest acceptance at 47% ([ScienceDaily](https://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2019/03/190312091912.htm)). This acceptance perpetuates the cycle of abuse and hinders reporting and intervention efforts.

## Prevalence in Specific Countries and Contexts

### India and South Asia

- Up to 25,000 women die annually due to bride burning, a form of dowry-related murder, in the Indian subcontinent ([Eastern Upper Peninsula ISD](https://www.eupschools.org/)).
- India records approximately 20 dowry deaths every day ([The Guardian](https://www.theguardian.com/)).
- Pakistan sees about 5,000 lethal domestic abuse deaths annually, with up to 89% of women experiencing some form of abuse ([New Internationalist](https://newint.org/)).

### Africa

- In the Democratic Republic of Congo, 53% of women have experienced marital rape ([ReliefWeb](https://reliefweb.int/)).
- South Africa reports that nearly 20% of women have experienced sexual intimate partner violence, and 50% of men admit to committing intimate partner violence ([CSVR & BBC](https://www.bbc.com/)).
- Somalia experiences 72% of gender-based violence cases between spouses ([UNDP](https://www.undp.org/)).

### United States

- Nearly one in four women and one in seven men experience severe physical violence by an intimate partner during their lifetime ([CDC](https://www.cdc.gov/violenceprevention/intimatepartnerviolence/index.html)).
- Approximately 4.8 million physical assaults and rapes by intimate partners occur annually among American women ([National Organization for Women](https://now.org/)).
- 12% of intimate partner violence cases involve male victims ([Office of Justice Programs](https://www.ojp.gov/)).

### Canada

- About 8% of women and 7% of men reported experiencing at least one incident of violence by a current or former partner in the preceding five years ([Statistics Canada](https://www.statcan.gc.ca/)).
- Indigenous populations face higher rates, with 20% of Aboriginal women and 13% of Aboriginal men reporting spousal violence ([Statistics Canada](https://www.statcan.gc.ca/)).
- Spousal abuse victims represent 18% of all violent offence victims reported to police ([Statistics Canada](https://www.statcan.gc.ca/)).

## Demographic and Social Factors Affecting Prevalence

### Gender and Age

Women are disproportionately affected by spousal abuse, both in prevalence and severity. For example, women are more likely to experience severe violence, such as being beaten or choked, and are more likely to require medical attention ([Statistics Canada](https://www.statcan.gc.ca/)).

Young women aged 20 to 24 are at the greatest risk of nonfatal intimate partner violence ([Statistics Canada](https://www.statcan.gc.ca/)).

### Sexual Orientation and Gender Identity

- 54% of transgender individuals have been in abusive relationships, with higher rates of severe physical harm compared to the general population ([National Center for Transgender Equality](https://transequality.org/)).
- Bisexual women experience the highest rates of intimate partner violence at 61%, followed by lesbian women at 44% ([VAWnet](https://vawnet.org/)).

### Children and Witnessing Abuse

- Globally, up to 275 million children are exposed to domestic violence ([UNICEF](https://www.unicef.org/)).
- In the US, 1 in 15 children is exposed to intimate partner violence annually ([Futures Without Violence](https://www.futureswithoutviolence.org/)).

### Socioeconomic and Cultural Factors

Economic dependence, societal acceptance, and cultural norms significantly influence the prevalence and reporting of spousal abuse. For instance, in regions where dowry practices persist or where women have limited economic rights, abuse rates tend to be higher ([ScienceDaily](https://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2019/03/190312091912.htm)).

## Reporting and Underreporting

A significant challenge in assessing the true prevalence of spousal abuse is underreporting. Many victims do not report abuse due to fear, stigma, economic dependence, or cultural pressures.

- In the US, fewer than half of domestic violence incidents are reported to the police ([NCADV](https://ncadv.org/)).
- Globally, fewer than 40% of women who experience violence seek help, and less than 10% contact the police ([UN Women](https://www.unwomen.org/)).

## Impact of COVID-19 on Domestic Violence Prevalence

The COVID-19 pandemic and associated lockdowns have exacerbated domestic violence worldwide:

- Domestic violence reports in Hubei, China increased by 244% during February 2020 ([The Guardian](https://www.theguardian.com/)).
- Spain saw a 700% spike in domestic violence support requests in early April 2020 ([The Guardian](https://www.theguardian.com/)).
- Domestic violence crisis calls quadrupled in Canada after lockdowns ([BWSS](https://www.bwss.org/)).

These increases are attributed to factors such as social isolation, economic stress, and reduced access to support services.

