## Conclusion and Opinion

Spousal abuse remains a highly prevalent and serious issue worldwide, affecting millions of individuals regardless of geography, culture, or socioeconomic status. The data consistently show that women bear the brunt of intimate partner violence, both in terms of prevalence and severity. While some regions report lower prevalence rates, these figures may be influenced by underreporting and cultural factors that discourage disclosure.

The persistence of societal acceptance of domestic violence in many parts of the world, combined with economic and cultural barriers, perpetuates the cycle of abuse. The COVID-19 pandemic has further highlighted the vulnerability of victims by increasing the incidence of domestic violence globally.

Given the extensive evidence, it is clear that spousal abuse is not only common but also deeply entrenched in many societies. Efforts to combat it must address cultural norms, improve economic empowerment for women, enhance legal protections, and expand support services. Accurate data collection and encouraging reporting are essential to understanding and ultimately reducing its prevalence.

